<article>
    <h1>LIFE HACKS</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201001/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-01"><time>2020-10-01</time></a>
        - <span>CLASSIFIED&#xAD;S</span>
        - <span role="byline">By JUSTIN FRAN&#xAD;CIS CHUA By JUSTIN FRAN&#xAD;CIS CHUA</span>
    </section>

    <p>You get a life hack. You get a life hack. YOU get a life hack! Ev­ery­one loves a good life hack, right?</p>
    <p>In case it is not clear enough, this piece will be on life hacks. So, life hacks. “A strat­egy or tech­nique adopted in or­der to man­age one's time and daily ac­tiv­i­ties in a more ef­ficient way.'' The more un­con­ven­tional, the bet­ter, it seems.</p>
    <p>The fol­low­ing are a few in­ge­nious ways you can adopt to make life a lit­tle less chal­leng­ing and a whole lot more fun.</p>
    <p>GET TOASTY</p>
    <p>To en­joy a per­fectly toasted sandwich, place both slices of bread in a sin­gle toaster slot. This way, the bread gets warm and crispy on the out­side, but stays soft and chewy on the in­side.</p>
    <p>NAIL IT</p>
    <p>Clip­ping fin­ger­nails and toe­nails can be a messy af­fair. To curb this, sim­ply wrap the in­side of your nail clip­per with scotch tape. By do­ing so, stray nails should stick to the tape, mean­ing you get to scratch those pesky fa­cial pim­ples once more with peace of mind.</p>
    <p>SAFETY FIRST</p>
    <p>Have you ever felt the sear­ing burn of a seat belt buckle? If you have ever made the mis­take of park­ing your car in an un­shel­tered area on a hot day, then chances are you have. To avoid be­ing hurt by the very de­vice that is de­signed to save you, click your belt buckle into its socket so that the metal sec­tion does not get di­rect ex­po­sure to sun­light.</p>

